      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can I contact the ombudsman if my loved one hasn't given permission?",
          "answer": "Yes, family members can contact the ombudsman on behalf of residents. However, the ombudsman will need to speak with your loved one directly to investigate complaints, as residents have the right to control their own advocacy process. The ombudsman can also provide general information about facility rights and policies without your loved one's direct involvement."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if the facility retaliates against my loved one for filing a complaint?",
          "answer": "Retaliation against residents for filing complaints is illegal under federal and state law. The ombudsman is trained to handle these situations and will work to protect your loved one from any form of retaliation. Document any suspected retaliation immediately and report it to the ombudsman, who can escalate to state licensing agencies if necessary."
        },
        {
          "question": "How is this different from calling the facility's administration directly?",
          "answer": "The ombudsman is an independent advocate not employed by the facility, giving them objectivity that internal staff may lack. Ombudsmen have special legal authority to investigate complaints, access facility records, and represent resident interests to state agencies. They also understand complex regulations that facilities must follow, making them more effective than family members navigating facility bureaucracy alone."
        }
      ],
